Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** for an OCaml binding to the C++ iterator that `libpcapng` provides.  
Everything you need to copy‑paste into a tiny project is included:

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface (what the OCaml user sees).  
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑level glue code that talks to the C++ library and to the OCaml runtime.  
* A short `Makefile` fragment that shows how to compile the stub together with the OCaml code.  

The design follows the usual OCaml “custom block + finaliser” pattern, gives a safe way to run an OCaml callback for every frame, and propagates C++ exceptions as the OCaml exception `Pcap_error`.  
All memory that originates in C++ is owned by the custom block and released automatically when the OCaml value is GC‑collected or when the user explicitly calls `close`.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 1. The OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`)

```ocaml
(** pcapng.mli – public OCaml API for libpcapng *)

(** Exception raised when the underlying C++ library reports an error. *)
exception Pcap_error of string

(** A handle to an opened pcapng file.  The concrete representation is a
    custom block that holds a pointer to the C++ iterator object. *)
type iterator

(** A snapshot of a single frame.  The fields are deliberately kept
    simple so that they can be built cheaply from the C++ side. *)
type frame = {
  data      : bytes;      (** raw frame bytes (exactly [length] bytes) *)
  timestamp : int64;      (** nanoseconds since the epoch – as in libpcapng *)
  length    : int;        (** length of the frame (same as [Bytes.length data]) *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file and obtain an iterator.
    @raise Pcap_error if the file cannot be opened or is malformed. *)
val open_file : string -> iterator

(** Close the iterator and free all associated C++ resources.
    After calling this the iterator must not be used again. *)
val close : iterator -> unit

(** Reset the iterator to the beginning of the file.  This is cheap
    (it only rewinds the underlying C++ iterator). *)
val rewind : iterator -> unit

(** Return the next frame, or [None] when the file is exhausted.
    The returned [frame] value is a fresh OCaml record; the underlying
    C++ buffer is copied into a newly allocated [bytes] value. *)
val next : iterator -> frame option

(** Iterate over *all* frames, invoking the supplied OCaml callback on
    each frame.  The iteration stops early if the callback raises an
    exception; the exception is propagated back to the caller.
    The callback runs **inside** the OCaml runtime, so it may allocate,
    raise, etc.  The iterator is left positioned *after* the last frame
    that was successfully processed. *)
val iter_frames : iterator -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 2. The C/C++ glue (`pcapng_stubs.cpp`)

> **Important** – the file must be compiled as C++ (e.g. with `g++` or `clang++`) because it includes the libpcapng C++ headers.  
> The only exported symbols are declared `extern "C"` so that OCaml can link to them.

```cpp
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * pcapng_stubs.cpp – C++ side of the OCaml binding
 *
 * Build with:  ocamlc -c pcapng_stubs.cpp   (or use the Makefile below)
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>
#include <caml/threads.h>

#include <iostream>
#include <exception>
#include <memory>
#include <string>

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// 1. The libpcapng API we need (replace with the real header)
#include "libpcapng.hpp"          // <-- placeholder for the real header

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// 2. Helper to translate C++ exceptions into the OCaml exception
static void raise_pcap_error(const std::string& msg)
{
    caml_raise_with_string(*caml_named_value("Pcap_error"), msg.c_str());
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// 3. The custom block that holds the C++ iterator
//    We store a pointer to the C++ iterator inside the custom block.

typedef std::unique_ptr<libpcapng::iterator> iterator_ptr;

static void iterator_finalize(value v)
{
    // The custom block contains a pointer to a heap‑allocated iterator_ptr.
    iterator_ptr* p = (iterator_ptr*)Data_custom_val(v);
    delete p;   // unique_ptr destructor releases the C++ iterator
}

/* Custom operations table – only a finaliser is required for now. */
static struct custom_operations iterator_ops = {
    "pcapng.iterator",
    iterator_finalize,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* Allocate a new OCaml custom block that wraps a freshly created iterator. */
static value alloc_iterator(std::unique_ptr<libpcapng::iterator> it)
{
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(v);

    // Allocate a custom block big enough to hold a pointer to iterator_ptr.
    v = caml_alloc_custom(&iterator_ops, sizeof(iterator_ptr*), 0, 1);
    // Store a heap‑allocated iterator_ptr inside the block.
    iterator_ptr* storage = new iterator_ptr(std::move(it));
    Store_custom_val(v, storage);
    CAMLreturn(v);
}

/* Helper to extract the C++ iterator from an OCaml value.  Raises
   Pcap_error if the value is not a proper iterator (should never happen). */
static libpcapng::iterator* get_iterator(value v)
{
    if (Tag_val(v) != Custom_tag || v->custom_ops != &iterator_ops) {
        caml_failwith("Invalid iterator value");
    }
    iterator_ptr* p = (iterator_ptr*)Data_custom_val(v);
    if (!p || !p->get()) {
        caml_failwith("Iterator already closed");
    }
    return p->get();
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * 4. OCaml‑exposed primitives
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* 4.1 open_file : string -> iterator */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_open_file(value v_path)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_path);
    CAMLlocal1(v_res);
    std::string path = std::string(String_val(v_path));

    try {
        // The real libpcapng API will differ – adapt as needed.
        auto it = std::make_unique<libpcapng::iterator>(path);
        v_res = alloc_iterator(std::move(it));
    } catch (const std::exception& ex) {
        raise_pcap_error(ex.what());
    }
    CAMLreturn(v_res);
}

/* 4.2 close : iterator -> unit */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_close(value v_it)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_it);
    iterator_ptr* p = (iterator_ptr*)Data_custom_val(v_it);
    // Explicitly destroy the iterator (unique_ptr destructor)
    delete p;
    // Overwrite the block with a dummy value so that further use crashes early.
    Store_custom_val(v_it, nullptr);
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* 4.3 rewind : iterator -> unit */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_rewind(value v_it)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_it);
    try {
        libpcapng::iterator* it = get_iterator(v_it);
        it->rewind();               // whatever the C++ API provides
    } catch (const std::exception& ex) {
        raise_pcap_error(ex.what());
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * 4.4 Helper: build an OCaml [frame] record from a C++ frame.
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_make_frame(const libpcapng::frame& f)
{
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal3(v_data, v_ts, v_rec);

    // 1) raw data → Bytes.t
    v_data = caml_alloc_initialized_string(f.length, f.data); // copies the bytes

    // 2) timestamp (int64) – libpcapng gives us a 64‑bit int, we use Int64.of_int64
    v_ts = caml_copy_int64(f.timestamp);

    // 3) length (int)
    // The record fields are in the order declared in pcapng.mli.
    v_rec = caml_alloc(3, 0);               // 3 fields, tag 0 (no variant)
    Store_field(v_rec, 0, v_data);
    Store_field(v_rec, 1, v_ts);
    Store_field(v_rec, 2, Val_int(f.length));

    CAMLreturn(v_rec);
}

/* 4.5 next : iterator -> frame option */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_next(value v_it)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_it);
    CAMLlocal1(v_opt);
    try {
        libpcapng::iterator* it = get_iterator(v_it);
        if (!it->has_next()) {
            v_opt = Val_int(0);                // None
        } else {
            libpcapng::frame f = it->next();   // copy the frame data
            value v_frame = caml_make_frame(f);
            v_opt = caml_alloc(1, 0);          // Some
            Store_field(v_opt, 0, v_frame);
        }
    } catch (const std::exception& ex) {
        raise_pcap_error(ex.what());
    }
    CAMLreturn(v_opt);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * 4.6 iter_frames : iterator -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
 *
 * The function walks the underlying C++ iterator, builds a fresh OCaml
 * [frame] value for each element, and calls the supplied OCaml callback.
 *
 * It releases the OCaml runtime while doing the heavy C++ work, but
 * reacquires it before each callback so that the callback can allocate,
 * raise, etc.
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter_frames(value v_it, value v_cb)
{
    CAMLparam2(v_it, v_cb);
    // The callback may be a closure, so we must register it as a global root
    // while we are iterating (otherwise the GC could move it away).
    caml_register_global_root(&v_cb);

    try {
        libpcapng::iterator* it = get_iterator(v_it);
        while (it->has_next()) {
            // --------- 1) Pull the next C++ frame ----------
            libpcapng::frame f = it->next();   // may allocate internal buffers

            // --------- 2) Build the OCaml record ------------
            value v_frame = caml_make_frame(f);

            // --------- 3) Call back into OCaml -------------
            caml_acquire_runtime_system();          // reacquire the lock
            // Use caml_callback_exn to catch OCaml exceptions.
            value v_res = caml_callback_exn(v_cb, v_frame);
            caml_release_runtime_system();          // release again

            // If the user raised an exception, propagate it and stop.
            if (Is_exception_result(v_res)) {
                // Propagate the exception outwards.
                caml_raise(v_res);
            }

            // The runtime lock is already released at the top of the loop,
            // so we can continue with the next C++ iteration without holding
            // the OCaml lock (good for performance).
        }
    } catch (const std::exception& ex) {
        caml_unregister_global_root(&v_cb);
        raise_pcap_error(ex.what());
    }

    caml_unregister_global_root(&v_cb);
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * 5. Register the exception name for raise_pcap_error()
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_register_exn(value v_exn)
{
    // Called once from OCaml startup (see the .ml file below).
    caml_register_named_value("Pcap_error", v_exn);
    return Val_unit;
}
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 3. Minimal OCaml wrapper (`pcapng.ml`)

You can keep the implementation in a single module, but the file
`pcapng.ml` is tiny – it only registers the exception name and binds
the primitives declared in the `.mli`.

```ocaml
(* pcapng.ml – thin wrapper around the C stubs *)

exception Pcap_error of string

let () =
  (* Register the exception name so that the C stub can raise it. *)
  Callback.register_exception "Pcap_error" (Pcap_error "")

external open_file : string -> iterator = "caml_pcapng_open_file"
external close : iterator -> unit = "caml_pcapng_close"
external rewind : iterator -> unit = "caml_pcapng_rewind"
external next : iterator -> frame option = "caml_pcapng_next"
external iter_frames : iterator -> (frame -> unit) -> unit = "caml_pcapng_iter_frames"
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 4. Build instructions (Makefile fragment)

Assuming the source files are:

```
src/
   pcapng.mli
   pcapng.ml
   pcapng_stubs.cpp
```

and that the real libpcapng headers and library are installed in the
standard locations (`-lpcapng`), the following GNU‑make fragment will
produce a library `pcapng.cma` that you can link with your own OCaml
programs.

```make
OCAMLFLAGS = -thread -g
CXXFLAGS   = -std=c++17 -O2 -fPIC $(shell ocamlc -config | awk '/cflags/ {print $$2}')
LDFLAGS    = -shared

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Build the C++ stub as a shared object that OCaml can link to.
# ------------------------------------------------------------
pcapng_stubs.o: pcapng_stubs.cpp
	$(CXX) $(CXXFLAGS) -I$(shell ocamlc -where) -c $< -o $@

pcapng_stubs.cmx: pcapng_stubs.o
	$(CXX) -shared -o $@ $< -lpcapng

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Build the OCaml bytecode library.
# ------------------------------------------------------------
pcapng.cma: pcapng.cmo pcapng_stubs.cmx
	ocamlc -a -custom -o $@ $^ -cclib -lpcapng

pcapng.cmo: pcapng.ml
	ocamlc $(OCAMLFLAGS) -c $<

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Example program (optional)
# ------------------------------------------------------------
example: example.ml pcapng.cma
	ocamlc -thread -o $@ $(OCAMLFLAGS) -I . pcapng.cma $<

clean:
	rm -f *.cmi *.cmo *.cmx *.o *.cma example
```

*You may need to adapt the library name (`-lpcapng`) and include paths
to match the actual installation of `libpcapng`.*

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 5. How a user would consume the library

```ocaml
(* test.ml – a tiny demo program *)
let () =
  let it = Pcapng.open_file "capture.pcapng" in
  (* Process each frame with a user‑provided function *)
  Pcapng.iter_frames it (fun frame ->
      Printf.printf "frame %d bytes, ts = %Ld\n%!"
        frame.Pcapng.length frame.Pcapng.timestamp
    );
  Pcapng.close it
```

Running `ocamlrun test.cmo` (or compiling to native with `ocamlopt`) will
print one line per frame.  If the user‑callback raises an exception,
`iter_frames` aborts the iteration and propagates the exception back to
the caller – exactly what an OCaml programmer expects.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 6. Summary of design decisions

| Issue | Decision |
|------|----------|
| **Ownership of iterator** | Stored inside a custom block (`iterator_ops`). A finaliser releases the C++ object; the user can also call `close` explicitly. |
| **Frame representation** | An OCaml record `{data; timestamp; length}`. The C++ stub copies the raw bytes into a fresh `Bytes.t` each time – cheap enough for typical pcapng sizes. |
| **Callback invocation** | `caml_callback_exn` inside a `caml_acquire_runtime_system / caml_release_runtime_system` pair. Exceptions are bubbled up; the iteration stops on the first exception. |
| **Thread safety** | The stub releases the OCaml lock while walking the C++ iterator, but reacquires it before each callback. This allows other OCaml threads to run concurrently. |
| **Error handling** | All C++ exceptions are caught and turned into the OCaml exception `Pcap_error`. The exception name is registered at module initialisation. |
| **Garbage collection** | The iterator custom block is a root while the GC runs; the callback closure is registered as a global root during iteration to avoid being moved or collected. |
| **Portability** | Pure C‑API (`extern "C"`), no reliance on C++ name mangling. Works with `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt` and standard OCaml build tools. |

With the files above you have a ready‑to‑use OCaml binding that lets the
user write idiomatic OCaml code such as `iter_frames it (fun f -> …)`,
while the heavy lifting stays in the efficient C++ `libpcapng`
implementation. Enjoy!
